ttp://gtr.ukri.org:80/projects?ref=RES-000-22-1454"><gtr:id>4B3104E2-D8F0-4752-93D6-55AAA95BBE40</gtr:id><gtr:title>Evaluating the effects of 'Best Practice' HRM in Local Government.</gtr:title><gtr:status>Closed</gtr:status><gtr:grantCategory>Research Grant</gtr:grantCategory><gtr:grantReference>RES-000-22-1454</gtr:grantReference><gtr:abstractText>&lt;p>&lt;strong>Aims&lt;/strong>&lt;/p>

&lt;p>To examine the impact of best practice human resource management on public sector workers and organisational performance.&lt;/p>

&lt;p>&lt;strong>Objectives&lt;/strong>&lt;/p>

&lt;ol>
 

 &lt;li>To evaluate the effects of best practice human resource management on performance outcomes in local government organisations;&lt;br />&lt;/li>

 &lt;li>To test whether the outcomes of best practice human resource management can be regarded as beneficial to employers (organisations) and employees;&lt;br />&lt;/li>

 &lt;li>To explain the different approaches taken to the adoption of best practice human resource management in local government organisations.&lt;/li>
&lt;/ol>

&lt;p>&lt;strong>Brief description of research project&lt;/strong>&lt;/p>

&lt;p>This research will evaluate the effects of ?best practice? human research management on individual and organisational performance outcomes in local government in Wales. The study will collect a range of outcomes of concern to both managers and employees through qualitative and quantitative research design. First a survey of staff attitudes and management practice will be undertaken across all participating local authority service departments. After analysing the survey data, a selected number of interviews with a cross-section of the workforce will be undertaken along with documentary analysis of policy directives. This approach is intended to provide context-specific information relating to HR practice and performance. As such, these data will assess whether HR practice leads to beneficial outcomes for organisations and workers ? outcomes that have largely been assumed rather than empirically tested.&lt;/p></gtr:abstractText><gtr:fund><gtr:end>2008-02-29</gtr:end><gtr:funder url="http://gtr.ukri.org:80/organisation/924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE"><gtr:id>924BE15C-91F2-4AAD-941A-3F338324B6AE</gtr:id><gtr:name>ESRC</gtr:name></gtr:funder><gtr:start>2006-01-01</gtr:start><gtr:type>INCOME_ACTUAL</gtr:type><gtr:valuePounds>30730</gtr:valuePounds></gtr:fund><gtr:output><gtr:artisticAndCreativeProductOutputs/><gtr:collaborationOutputs/><gtr:disseminationOutputs/><gtr:exploitationOutputs/><gtr:furtherFundingOutputs/><gtr:impactSummaryOutputs/><gtr:intellectualPropertyOutputs/><gtr:otherResearchOutputs/><gtr:policyInfluenceOutputs/><gtr:productOutputs/><gtr:researchDatabaseAndModelOutputs/><gtr:researchMaterialOutputs/><gtr:softwareAndTechnicalProductOutputs/><gtr:spinOutOutputs/></gtr:output><gtr:publications/><gtr:identifiers><gtr:identifier type="RES">RES-000-22-1454</gtr:identifier><gtr:identifier type="RCUK">RES-000-22-1454</gtr:identifier></gtr:identifiers><gtr:healthCategories/><gtr:researchActivities/><gtr:researchSubjects><gtr:researchSubject><gtr:id>5E